title.narrative: Relevant MDAs and select LGAs and communities have enhanced capacities to deliver quality and relevant formal basic education

description.narrative: National pre-primary and primary in-service education and training (INSET) modules are now available in all 16,149 government primary schools, aligning in-service teacher training for over 30,000 pre-primary teachers. Teacher competencies have been enhanced through the adoption and use of the standard I & II teachers approved National School-Based Continuous Professional Development Framework. The use of these standards will help teachers effectively delivery early grade curriculum for benefit of over 10.6 million preprimary and primary school children nationally. Additionally, Tanzania now has a National Strategy for Parenting and Family Care launched by government, expanding multi-sectoral parenting education. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:12/11/2019

title.narrative: Education systems are implementing a minimum package of interventions to promote learning outcomes including early learning

baseline.value: High impact intervention package not defined jointly by all partners

target.value: 2021:High impact intervention package scaled up in 75% of targeted LGAs

actual.value: 2019:High impact package defined and agreed with Development partners. About 26% of LGAs in MINS are implementing a set of School/Classroom infrastructure including WASH, Teacher Availability and development (INSET) and Provision of learning material.

System Strengthening - Early learning - Existence of national policy, leadership and budget for early learning - score (1-4), see guidance

baseline.value: Score 3: Early learning policy has been developed, as evidenced by official documentation (e.g. Education Sector Plan).

target.value: 2021:Score 4: Early learning policy has been developed, as evidenced by official documentation (e.g. Education Sector Plan)

actual.value: 2019:Preprimary education is integrated in the ESDP. However, standards, quality assurance and data collection mechanism on PPE is embedded in the primary education sub-sector. Financial and human resources to PPE are not need-based planned though there are some consideration of early learning models.
